  "title": "Non-existent Limits",
  "body": " Non-existent Limits  Many limit values do not exist. Sometimes the non-existence is caused by the function value either increasing without bound or decreasing without bound. In these special cases we use the symbols and to communicate the non-existence of the limits. Figures can be used to illustrate some ways in which we communicate the non-existence of these types of limits.   In we could (correctly) write  In we could (correctly) write  In we could (correctly) write There is no shorthand way of communicating the non-existence of the two-sided limit .       a plot of a function; the curve comes in from the left low on the graph at about y=-6.5; it is flat for a while, but when it reaches the x-axis it begins to curve up steeply; there is a dashed vertical line at x=2, and the curve bends upward until it is almost parallel with this vertical line; the curve is quite close to this vertical line (but still to its left) when the curve leaves the top of the graph; the curve picks up again on the other side of the vertical line, coming in downward from the top of the graph a little to the right of the vertical line; it moves almost straight downward and slightly to the right for a while, crossing below the x-axis; around when it reaches the point (3,-5.5), it flattens as it continues to move rightward        a plot of a function; the curve comes in from the left high on the graph at about y=6.5; it is flat for a while, but when it reaches about x=2 it begins to curve down steeply; there is a dashed vertical line at x=4, and the curve bends downward until it is almost parallel with this vertical line; the curve is quite close to this vertical line (but still to its left) when the curve leaves the bottom of the graph; the curve picks up again on the other side of the vertical line, coming in upward from the bottom of the graph a little to the right of the vertical line; it moves almost straight upward and slightly to the right for a while, crossing above the x-axis; around when it reaches the point (5,5.5), it flattens as it continues to move rightward        a plot of a function; the curve comes in from the left low on the graph at about y=-6.5; it is flat for a short while, but when it reaches about x=-5, it begins to curve up steeply; there is a dashed vertical line at x=-3, and the curve bends upward until it is almost parallel with this vertical line; the curve is quite close to this vertical line (but still to its left) when the curve leaves the top of the graph; the curve picks up again on the other side of the vertical line, coming in upward from the bottom of the graph a little to the right of the vertical line; it moves almost straight upward and slightly to the right for a while, crossing above the x-axis; around when it reaches the point (-2,5.5), it flattens as it continues to move rightward        In the plane provided, draw the graph of a single function, , that satisfies each of the following limit statements. Make sure that you draw the necessary asymptotes and that you label each asymptote with its equation.       a blank Cartesian grid, with x-axis covering the interval from -7 to 7, and y-axis covering the interval from -7 to 7        "
