  "body": " Instantaneous Velocity  Most of the focus in was on average rates of change. While the idea of rates of change at one specific instant was alluded to, we couldn't explore that idea formally because we hadn't yet talked about limits. Now that we have covered average rates of change and limits we can put those two ideas together to discuss rates of change at specific instances in time.  Suppose that an object is tossed into the air in such a way that the elevation of the object (measured in ) is given by the function defined by where is the amount of time that has passed since the object was tossed (measured in ). Let's determine the velocity of the object seconds into this flight.  Recall that the difference quotient gives us the average velocity for the object between the times and . So long as is positive, we can think of as the length of the time interval. To infer the velocity exactly seconds into the flight we need the time interval as close to as possible; this is done using the appropriate limit in .   From this we can infer that the velocity of the object seconds into its flight is -24 . From that we know that the object is falling at a speed of 24 .       Suppose that an object is tossed into the air so that its elevation (measured in ) is given by , where is the amount of time that has passed since the object was tossed (measured in ).   Average Velocities                                      Evaluate showing each step in the simplification process (as illustrated in ).    What is the unit for the value calculated in and what does the value (including unit) tell you about the motion of the object?    Copy onto your paper and compute and record the missing values. Do these values support your answer to ?     "
