  "title": "Nondifferentiability",
  "body": " Nondifferentiability  A function is said to be nondifferentiable at any value where its first derivative is undefined. There are three graphical behaviors that lead to non-differentiability.   is nondifferentiable at if is discontinuous at .  is nondifferentiable at if the slope of is different from the left and right at .  is nondifferentiable at if has a vertical tangent line at .      Consider the function shown in . Please note that has a vertical tangent line at .      a graph of a function whose curve has two segments; the first segment enters from the left at about (-7,4), moving rightward and slightly downward; it becomes more and more steep until at x=-4, it is briefly vertical; it then loses its steepness and continues moving downward and to the right reaching (-3,-1); here it sharply bends into a straight line, connecting to (-1,3); there is a solid dot at (-1,3), and this segment ends here; the second segment begins at (-1,-5) with a hollow dot; fromt here it connects to (4,5) with a straight line; here it sharply bends downward to a straight line with slope -4, and exits the graph near the lower right corner        a blank graph with x-axis and y-axis each ranging from -7 to 7        There are four values where is nondifferentiable; what are these values?    Draw onto .      Consider the function shown in .      the graph of a periodic function; the curve enters from the left at about (-7,2.5), and curves down to (-5,-2); here it sharply changes direction, moving back upward as it travels to the right; it gradually loses its steepness until it reaches (-2.5,3), where it smoothly transitions from an increasing curve to a decreasing one, and then falls down to (0,-2); here it sharply changes direction again, and repeats the same \"camel hump\" shape that was just described; it repreats this again, exiting the graph at about (7,2.5); all together there were three visible sharp turning points, at (-5,-2), (0,-2), and (5,-2); and there were two visible flat points, at (-2.5,3) and (2.5,3)        only part of a curve is plotted; the curve has a hollow dot at (-5,3); then it moves rightward, curving more and more downward, until it reaches (-2.5,0); here the visible portion abruptly stops, but the reader is meant to continue drawing it        has been drawn onto over the interval . Use the piecewise symmetry and periodic behavior of to help you draw the remainder of over .    What six-syllable word applies to at , , and ?    What five-syllable and six-syllable words apply to at , , and ?     "
