  "title": "Higher Order Derivatives",
  "body": " Higher Order Derivatives  Seeing as the first derivative of is a function in its own right, must have its own first derivative. The first derivative of is the second derivative of and is symbolized as ( double-prime). Likewise, ( triple-prime) is the first derivative of , the second derivative of , and the third derivative of .   All of the graphical relationships you've established between and work their way down the derivative chain; this is illustrated in .   Relationships between , , and      When is  is    When is  is    When is  is    Positive  Increasing    Negative  Decreasing    Constantly Zero  Constant    Increasing  Concave Up    Decreasing  Concave Down    Constant  Linear        Extrapolating from , what must be true about over intervals where is, respectively: positive, negative, or constantly zero?    A function, , and its first three derivatives are shown in Figures , although not in that order. Determine which curve is which function ( ).      a function's curve that starts at the origin, initially moves almost flat to the right, but steadily increasing in steepness until about (0.5,1.5), where it begins losing steepness; it flattens out at about (1.1,1.3), reaching a peak; then it descends, crossing the x-axis at about 1.8, and moving down to about (2.7,-2), where it smoothly flattens out and turns around, moving upward, again crossing the x-axis at about 3.8, and then exiting the graph at about (4,0.3)        a function's curve that starts at -1 on the y-axis, initially moveing almost flat to the right, but eventually curving upward; it crosses the x-axis at about 1.75, and continues rising to a peak at about (2.8,1), where it smoothly bends back downward, exiting the graph at a little above (4,0)        a function's curve that starts at the origin with an upward slope, reach a peak at about (0.6,2) before smoothly bending downward; it crosses the x-axis at about 1.1, continuing downward to reach a low point of about (1.8,-3.5); the curve flattens out here and smoothly bends back upward, again crossing the x-axis at about 2.7, and continuing upward to a peak at about (3.4,2.3); the curve then smoothly bends back downward and exits the graph at about (4,1.5)        a function's curve that starts at the origin, initially moves almost flat to the right, but steadily increasing in steepness until about (1.2,0.8), where the curve begins to lose steepness; it reaches a peak at about (1.8,1.3), bending back down and corssing the x-axis at about 2.8; the curev continues downward and to the right, but flattening out as it exits the graph at about (4,-1)         Three containers are shown in Figures . Each of the following questions are in reference to these containers.      a rectangular prism        a prism-like shape, with a top that is a large square and a bottom that is a small square        a prism-like shape, with a top that is a small square and a bottom that is a large square        Suppose that water is being poured into each of the containers at a constant rate. Let , , and be the heights (measured in ) of the liquid in containers respectively, seconds after the water began to fill the containers. What would you expect the sign to be on the second derivative functions , , and while the containers are being filled? (Hint: Think about the shape of the curves , , and .)    Suppose that water is being drained from each of the containers at a constant rate. Let , , and be the heights (measured in ) of the liquid remaining in the containers seconds after the water began to drain. What would you expect the sign to be on the second derivative functions , , and while the containers are being drained?     During the recession of 2008 2009, the total number of employed Americans decreased every month. One month a talking head on the television made the observation that at least the second derivative was positive this month. Why was it a good thing that the second derivative was positive?    During the early 1980s the problem was inflation. Every month the average price for a gallon of milk was higher than the month before. Was it a good thing when the second derivative of this function was positive? Explain.    "
