  "title": "Antiderivatives",
  "body": " Antiderivatives  The derivative continuum can be expressed backwards as well as forwards. When you move from function to function in the reverse direction the resultant functions are called antiderivatives and the process is called antidifferentiation . These relationships are shown in Figures and .   Differentiating     Antidifferentiating    There are (at least) two important differences between the differentiation chain and the antidifferentiation chain (besides their reversed order).   When you differentiate, the resultant function is unique. When you antidifferentiate, you do not get a unique function you get a family of functions; specifically, you get a set of parallel curves.  We introduce a new function in the antidifferentiation chain. We say that is an antiderivative of . This is where we stop in that direction; we do not have a variable name for an antiderivative of .   Since is considered an antiderivative of , it must be the case that is the first derivative of . Hence we can add to our derivative chain resulting in .   Differentiating        Each of the linear functions in has the same first derivative function.           Draw this common first derivative function onto and label it .    Each of the given lines is called what in relation to ?      The function is shown in . Reference this function in the following questions.                                At what values of is nondifferentiable?    At what values of are antiderivatives of nondifferentiable?    Draw onto the continuous antiderivative of that passes through the point . Note that every antiderivative of increases exactly one unit over the interval .    Because is not continuous, there are other antiderivatives of that pass through the point . Specifically, antiderivatives of may or may not be continuous at . Draw onto Figures and different antiderivatives of that pass through the point .     Recall that a function, , is periodic if there exists a constant, , with the property that for all values of in the domain of . The function is an example of a periodic function. Specifically, the function has a period of because over any interval of length the behavior of the function is exactly the same as it was the previous interval of length . A little more precisely, regardless of the value of .  Jasmine was thinking and told her lab assistant that derivatives and antiderivatives of periodic functions must also be periodic. Jasmine's lab assistant told her that she was half right. Which half did Jasmine have correct the part about the derivatives necessarily being periodic or the part about antiderivatives necessarily being periodic? Also, draw a function that illustrates that the other half of Jasmine's statement is not correct.    Consider the function shown in .                Let be an antiderivative of . Suppose that is continuous on , , and that the greatest value ever achieves is . Draw onto .      Answer the following questions in reference to a continuous function whose first derivative is shown in . You do not need to state how you made your determination; just state the interval(s) or values of that satisfy the stated property. Note: the correct answer to one or more of these questions may be There is no way of knowing.           Over what interval(s) is positive and increasing?    At what value(s) of is nondifferentiable?    Over what interval(s) is never negative?    At what value(s) of is every antiderivative of nondifferentiable?    Over what interval(s) does have a constant value?    Over what interval(s) is linear?    Over what interval(s) are antiderivatives of linear?    Over what interval(s) is never negative?     "
